Ω // –ó–∞–∫–æ–Ω–Ω–æ—Å—Ç—å. 2016. ‚Ññ 3. –°. 44‚Äì46. 9 –ö—É–ª–∏–∫–æ–≤–∞, –ú. –ú. –£—á–∞—Å—Ç–∏–µ —Ä–æ–¥–∏—Ç–µ–ª–µ–π –Ω–µ—Å–æ–≤–µ—Ä—à–µ–Ω–Ω–æ–ª–µ—Ç–Ω–∏—Ö –≤ –∫–∞—á–µ—Å—Ç–≤–µ –∑–∞–∫–æ–Ω–Ω—ã—Ö –ø—Ä–µ–¥—Å—Ç–∞–≤–∏—Ç–µ–ª–µ–π –≤ —É–≥–æ–ª–æ–≤–Ω–æ–º –ø—Ä–æ—Ü–µ—Å—Å–µ / –ú. –ú. –ö—É–ª–∏–∫–æ–≤–∞ // –°—É–¥—å—è. 2015. ‚Ññ 7. –°. 47‚Äì50. 10 –û —Å—É–¥–µ–±–Ω–æ–π –ø—Ä–∞–∫—Ç–∏–∫–µ –ø—Ä–∏–º–µ–Ω–µ–Ω–∏—è –∑–∞- –∫–æ–Ω–æ–¥–∞—Ç–µ–ª—å—Å—Ç–≤–∞, —Ä–µ–≥–ª–∞–º–µ–Ω—Ç–∏—Ä—É—é—â–µ–≥–æ –æ—Å–æ-–±–µ–Ω–Ω–æ—Å—Ç–∏ —É–≥–æ–ª–æ–≤–Ω–æ–π –æ—Ç–≤–µ—Ç—Å—Ç–≤–µ–Ω–Ω–æ—Å—Ç–∏ –∏ –Ω–∞–∫–∞–∑–∞–Ω–∏—è –Ω–µ—Å–æ–≤–µ—Ä—à–µ–Ω–Ω–æ–ª–µ—Ç–Ω–∏—Ö : –ø–æ—Å—Ç–∞–Ω–æ–≤- –ª–µ–Ω–∏–µ –ü–ª–µ–Ω—É–º–∞ –í–µ—Ä—Ö–æ–≤–Ω–æ–≥–æ –°—É–¥–∞ –†–§ –æ—Ç 01.02.2011 –≥. ‚Ññ 1 (–≤ —Ä–µ–¥. –æ—Ç 29.11.2016 –≥.) // –°–ø—Ä–∞–≤.-–ø—Ä–∞–≤. —Å–∏—Å—Ç–µ–º–∞ ¬´–ö–æ–Ω—Å—É–ª—å—Ç–∞–Ω—Ç–ü–ª—é—Å¬ª (–¥–∞—Ç–∞ –æ–±—Ä–∞—â–µ–Ω–∏—è 11.04.2020). 11 –õ–∞–º–∏–Ω—Ü–µ–≤–∞, –°. –ê. –ü—Ä–æ—Ü–µ—Å—Å—É–∞–ª—å- –Ω—ã–µ –≥–∞—Ä–∞–Ω—Ç–∏–∏ —Ä–µ–∞–ª–∏–∑–∞—Ü–∏–∏ –ø—Ä–∞–≤ –Ω–µ—Å–æ- –≤–µ—Ä—à–µ–Ω–Ω–æ–ª–µ—Ç–Ω–∏—Ö –≤ —É–≥–æ–ª–æ–≤–Ω–æ–º —Å—É–¥–æ–ø—Ä–æ- –∏–∑–≤–æ–¥—Å—Ç–≤–µ / –°. –ê. –õ–∞–º–∏–Ω—Ü–µ–≤–∞ // –°—É–¥—å—è. 2017. ‚Ññ 4. –°. 43‚Äì48. 12 –•–∏–º–∏—á–µ–≤–∞, –ì. –ü. –ù–µ—Å–æ–≤–µ—Ä—à–µ–Ω–Ω–æ–ª–µ—Ç- –Ω–∏–π –æ–±–≤–∏–Ω—è–µ–º—ã–π (–ø–æ–¥–æ–∑—Ä–µ–≤–∞–µ–º—ã–π) : –º–µ—Ä—ã –ø—Ä–µ—Å–µ—á–µ–Ω–∏—è / –ì. –ü. –•–∏–º–∏—á–µ–≤–∞ // –£–≥–æ–ª–æ–≤–Ω–æ–µ —Å—É–¥–æ–ø—Ä–æ–∏–∑–≤–æ–¥—Å—Ç–≤–æ. 2014. ‚Ññ 4. –°. 20‚Äì24. 13 –û—Å–Ω–æ–≤—ã —É–≥–æ–ª–æ–≤–Ω–æ–≥–æ —Å—É–¥–æ–ø—Ä–æ–∏–∑–≤–æ–¥- —Å—Ç–≤–∞ : —É—á–µ–±–Ω–∏–∫ –¥–ª—è –±–∞–∫–∞–ª–∞–≤—Ä–æ–≤ / –ø–æ–¥ —Ä–µ–¥. –í. –ê. –î–∞–≤—ã–¥–æ–≤–∞, –í. –í. –ï—Ä—à–æ–≤–∞. –ú. : –†–ì–£–ü, 2017. 444 c. 14 –û–±–∑–æ—Ä –ø—Ä–∞–∫—Ç–∏–∫–∏ —Ä–∞—Å—Å–º–æ—Ç—Ä–µ–Ω–∏—è —Å—É- –¥–∞–º–∏ —Ö–æ–¥–∞—Ç–∞–π—Å—Ç–≤ –æ–± –∏–∑–±—Ä–∞–Ω–∏–∏ –º–µ—Ä—ã –ø—Ä–µ- —Å–µ—á–µ–Ω–∏—è –≤ –≤–∏–¥–µ –∑–∞–∫–ª—é—á–µ–Ω–∏—è –ø–æ–¥ —Å—Ç—Ä–∞–∂—É –∏ –æ –ø—Ä–æ–¥–ª–µ–Ω–∏–∏ —Å—Ä–æ–∫–∞ —Å–æ–¥–µ—Ä–∂–∞–Ω–∏—è –ø–æ–¥ —Å—Ç—Ä–∞- –∂–µ–π : —É—Ç–≤. –ü—Ä–µ–∑–∏–¥–∏—É–º–æ–º –í–µ—Ä—Ö–æ–≤–Ω–æ–≥–æ –°—É–¥–∞ –†–§ 18.01.2017 –≥. // –°–ø—Ä–∞–≤.-–ø—Ä–∞–≤. —Å–∏—Å—Ç–µ–º–∞ ¬´–ö–æ–Ω—Å—É–ª—å—Ç–∞–Ω—Ç–ü–ª—é—Å¬ª (–¥–∞—Ç–∞ –æ–±—Ä–∞—â–µ–Ω–∏—è 11.04.2020).","output":"Criminal proceedings against minors are characterized by the existence of a complex set of additional guarantees for the protection of the rights and legitimate interests of the accused and the suspects. This is explained by, among other things, the need to implement generally recognized standards of justice into the national legal system, which has not left aside the production of criminal cases against minors [1]. It seems that the most significant from the point of view of implementing the basic right of a person being brought to criminal liability is the right to qualified legal aid, which in our case is transformed into the obligation of the investigator, the inquiry officer, to ensure the participation of a defender in all cases of preliminary investigation into the minor (paragraph 2 of part 1 of Article 51 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation). In this regard, the possibility of involving not only a lawyer, but also another person as a defender is discussed in the specialized literature. Thus, some proceduralists categorically object to the presence of even a potential possibility of involving unprofessional defenders to provide legal assistance to a minor, either in addition to a lawyer or instead of one, in the proceedings before a magistrate [2, p. 59]. Even more categorical is the assertion of the need to take into account the specialization of the lawyer when admitting him to the criminal process as a defender of a minor [3, p. 26]. A different approach is justified by the thesis that the quality of the assistance provided depends not on the professional affiliation of the person, but on his knowledge, skills, and practical experience [4, p. 75]. We believe that in deciding the issue at hand, it is necessary to start from the fact that the legislator indicates a lawyer as the only possible defender at the stage of pre-trial proceedings, which is additionally emphasized regarding to minors, as well as other defendants and suspects in paragraph 10 of the Resolution of the Plenum of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation of June 30, 2015 No. 29 [5], as well as repeatedly ascertained by the Constitutional Court of the Russian Federation, whose position is that the provision of unqualified legal assistance contradicts the tasks of justice and the obligation of the state to provide legal support to a person being brought to criminal liability, regardless of their age, social and property status, as well as other criteria [6]. Analysis of law enforcement practices allows us to affirm that, in general, the right to defense is provided to the minor defendant (suspect) in the proper volume, and its implementation is guaranteed by the investigator, the inquiry officer. According to the studied materials of criminal cases, a defender was admitted to the criminal process in all cases in accordance with the requirements of part 3 of Article 49 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation from the moment of: issuing a resolution on bringing the minor as an accused or initiating a criminal case against him; his actual detention as a suspect; the beginning of the implementation of other measures of procedural coercion or other procedural actions that affect the rights and freedoms of minors, including cases of verification of a crime report, that is, in fact, before conferring the procedural status of a suspect or accused to the minor. The most significant form of providing qualified legal assistance to a minor is the participation of a lawyer-defender in the production of investigative actions. The study of 43 materials of criminal cases showed that these are predominantly interrogations of minor suspects, defendants, as well as confrontations, identifications, and inspections of testimonies on the spot. During the production of the mentioned investigative actions, the defenders responded to violations of the rights of the suspects, challenged the questions of the investigator, which in their opinion could worsen the procedural position of the defendant, as well as causing emotional and psychological pressure on him, which was reflected in the protocols of the investigative actions. It should also be noted that the legislator has significantly expanded the defense's opportunities to participate in the proof by indicating the obligation to satisfy the relevant petitions for the attachment to the materials of the criminal case objects and documents that have probative value, as well as the conclusions of specialists obtained during studies initiated by the defense (paragraph 2.2 of Article 159 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation). An additional guarantee of protecting the interests of a minor is the participation of his legal representative in the criminal process, who in accordance with paragraph 12 of Article 5 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation involve the parents, adoptive parents, guardians or trustees of the minor suspect, defendant, representatives of institutions or organizations under whose care he is, tutelage and guardianship authorities. The participation of the named persons in the proceedings of the criminal case in this case is an imperative prescription of the legislator and does not depend on the will of either the law enforcement officer conducting the preliminary investigation or the minor defendant or suspect himself. However, in accordance with part 4 of Article 426 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation, an official is granted the right to dismiss a legal representative from participating in a criminal case if there are reasons to believe that his actions are detrimental to the interests of a minor suspect or defendant. In this case, another legal representative of the minor suspect or defendant is admitted to participate in the criminal case, which actualizes the question of the list of such persons, since the comparison of the provisions of part 1 of Article 437 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation (involvement of legal representatives in the production of compulsory medical measures) and Article 48 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation allows us to state a discrepancy in the respective lists. In the first case, it is wider because legal representatives are admitted as close relatives, including spouses, parents, children, adopters, adopted, native brothers and sisters, grandparents, grandchildren (paragraph 3 of Article 5 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation). Therefore, based on the provisions of Article 437 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation, the legal representatives of the minor suspect or defendant include native brothers and sisters, grandfather and grandmother. The question arises as to whom should be involved as a legal representative when implementing the provisions of part 4 of Article 426 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation? Following a literal interpretation of the law, it can be established that, in accordance with paragraph 12 of Article 5 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation, it is necessary to involve the guardianship and trusteeship authority, however, G.N. Smirnova makes a fair observation that this is contrary to the interests of a minor, since representatives of public authorities are indifferent to his fate, unlike close relatives [3, p. 28]. The fairness of this thesis is also evidenced by empirical analysis. Thus, out of 43 materials of criminal cases in 8 cases representatives of the guardianship and trusteeship authority were involved as legal representatives of a minor and in 3 of them they filed petitions for the consideration of a criminal case in a court hearing without their participation. There is no consensus in the specialized literature on this issue. Thus, for example, R.I. Zainullin indicates the need to resolve the issue of representation by means of a family agreement, and if this is not possible, the choice of a legal representative should be granted to the minor defendant or suspect [7, p. 4]. A.A. Andreykin holds a similar point of view, indicating regarding to a minor victim that his interest in the outcome of a criminal case allows the most effective resolution of the issue of a legal representative [8, p. 44]. We believe that in this case the arguments of those proceduralists who point to the ethical vices of such an approach are also justified, when a teenager is legally forced to make a choice, for example, between a father and a mother, while it is necessary to put not personal relationships, but the effectiveness of activities to protect the interests of a minor in the forefront [9, p. 49]. It seems that when resolving this issue, the following should be taken into account. Firstly, the legal representative, in the conditions of mandatory participation of a defender, provides not legal, but rather moral and psychological assistance to the minor, which implies the existence of some kind of confidential relationship between them. Secondly, he is obliged to act in the interests of the minor, as is quite obviously evidenced by the above positions of part 4 of Article 426 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation. Thirdly, a legal representative is endowed with a broad complex of rights, which, together with the rights provided to the defender, allows to optimally guarantee the protection of the interests of a minor. In this regard, it seems that if it is established that there are favorable living conditions and upbringing of a minor, which is an integral element of the subject of evidence, then the right to choose a legal representative should be granted to the family taking into account the opinion of a teenager. If, however, the situation is the opposite, then the choice of a legal representative should remain within the competence of the investigator, who collects information about family relationships not only from interested parties, but also from neighbors, educators, inspectors for juvenile affairs, etc. In this regard, we believe that the list of persons who can be legal representatives of a minor suspect, defendant, should be expanded by including in it, in addition to the persons indicated in paragraph 12 of Article 5 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation: - other, in addition to parents, close relatives of the minor (native brothers and sisters, grandfather, grandmother); - Close persons of the minor who are dear to them due to their personal relationship. In accordance with part 2 of Article 426 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation, in the pre-trial proceedings, a legal representative of the accused or suspect is endowed with certain rights: to know what the minor is suspected or accused of; to be present at the presentation of charges; to participate in the interrogation of a minor suspect or defendant, as well as with the permission of the investigator ‚Äì in other investigative actions carried out with his participation and the participation of a defender; to get acquainted with the protocols of investigative actions in which he participated, and make written remarks about the correctness and completeness of the records made in them; to file petitions and challenges, to bring complaints against actions (inaction) and decisions of the inquiry officer, the investigator, the prosecutor; to present evidence; after the end of the preliminary investigation to get acquainted with all the materials of the criminal case, to write out any information from it and in any volume. An analysis of the totality of the norms of the criminal procedural law, regulating the peculiarities of the preliminary investigation of criminal cases against minors, allows us to state certain difficulties in the implementation of some of the aforementioned rights of the legal representative. Thus, there is no doubt about the justification of the right to know about the essence of the accusations or suspicions presented to the minor. However, the mechanism for its implementation is practically not provided by law. Thus, in the current version of part 1 of Article 426 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation, a legal representative may be admitted to the process only from the moment of the first interrogation of a minor as a suspect or defendant, and at the same time the above rights are explained to him. Accordingly, a legal representative can find out about the essence of suspicion or accusation already in the course of the interrogation, but in no way earlier. Similar problems arise when implementing the right of a legal representative to be present during the presentation of charges because the first interrogation of a minor as a defendant follows the procedure for presenting charges, and does not precede it. We believe that the aforementioned contradictions would be resolved by changing the moment of admission of a legal representative to participate in the proceedings of a criminal case. In our opinion, it should depend not on the conduct of an investigative action, but on conferring the procedural status of a suspect or defendant to a minor, which allows drawing an analogy with the admission of a defender to the criminal process when the named subjects have an identical function performed in different forms, ‚Äì protection of the legal rights and interests of a minor. In this regard, we propose to express part 1 of Article 426 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation as follows: \\"Legal representatives of a minor suspect or defendant are admitted to participate in a criminal case based on a decision of an investigator, an inquiry officer, from the moment a decision is made to charge the minor as an accused or from the moment he is given the status of a suspect in accordance with the provisions of part 1 of Article 46 of this Code. When admitted to participate in a criminal case, they are explained the rights provided for by the second part of this article.\\" Age characteristics of the suspects, the accused in the cases considered require the use of special knowledge, which is implemented by involving a teacher or psychologist in the interrogation of the minor. In accordance with paragraph 9 of the Resolution of the Plenum of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation, these persons are mandatory for the production of interrogation of a minor aged 14 to 16 years, and at the age of 16 to 18 years ‚Äì provided that he suffers from a mental disorder or has mental retardation [10]. The procedural consequence of non-compliance with the prescription of Article 425 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation is the lack of evidentiary value of the testimonies obtained from the minor (part 2 of Article 75 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation). Speaking about the participation of a teacher and a psychologist in the production of interrogation of a minor, one cannot ignore the uncertainty of the procedural status of the named persons. Following the logic of the legislator, it can be assumed that they are introduced into the criminal process as specialists and accordingly have the entire set of rights and duties provided for by Article 58 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation. However, in accordance with part 5 of Article 425 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation, the teacher and the psychologist are endowed with a limited number of rights, directly related to the production of the interrogation: to ask questions to the minor suspect or defendant with the permission of the investigator or the inquiry officer; after the interrogation, to get acquainted with the protocol of the interrogation and make written observations on the correctness and completeness of the records made in it. Beyond the procedural status of the named persons, there remain such rights of a specialist as the right to refuse to participate in the proceedings of a criminal case if he does not possess the corresponding special knowledge; to bring complaints against actions (inaction) and decisions of the inquiry officer, the head of the inquiry unit, the head of the inquiry body, the inquiry body, the investigator, the prosecutor, and the court, limiting his rights (part 3 of Article 58 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation). We believe that the procedural position of a teacher and a psychologist needs to be improved not only from the point of view of the general logic of constructing the status of persons assisting in the proceedings of a criminal case, but also from the positions of an emerging trend towards the expansion of the boundaries of their participation in the proceedings of criminal cases against minors. Such participation has the nature of a pilot project and is characterized by the accompaniment of a criminal case from the moment of its initiation to the conduct of rehabilitation measures [11]. In this regard, we propose to express part 5 of Article 425 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation as follows: \\"A teacher and (or) a psychologist in the course of the production of interrogation of a minor exercise the rights provided for by part 3 of Article 58 of this Code.\\" The specificity of the preliminary investigation involving a minor as a participant in legal proceedings presupposes a special regime for the production of investigative actions. This concerns not only minors accused, suspects, but also victims and witnesses. The equality of the rights of the parties, declared as an element of the principle of adversarial proceedings (part 4 of Article 15 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation), in our view, implies equality of the procedural guarantees provided to all minors, regardless of their actual procedural status. A comparative analysis of the provisions of Article 191 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation and Article 425 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation allows us to highlight common guarantees of rights and legitimate interests of minor victims, witnesses, suspects, and accused when conducting an interrogation, namely: - limiting the duration of the named investigative action for the age group from 14 to 18 years to 2 hours without a break and the total duration during the day to no more than 4 hours; - participation of a teacher and a psychologist, which in the above-mentioned cases is mandatory; - the presence of a legal representative's right to be present during the investigative action involving a minor. At the same time, there are also significant, in our opinion, differences that are not justified by the presence of a minor's status as an accused (suspect). Thus, if a minor is a victim and a witness, then a special regime of production of investigative actions extends not only to interrogation but also to other verbal actions ‚Äì face-to-face confrontation, identification, and verification of testimonies. For a suspect, an accused, Article 425 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation mentions only the production of interrogation. In addition, in accordance with part 5 of Article 191 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation, video recording or filming, the materials of which are stored in a criminal case, are mandatory during the production of investigative actions involving a minor victim or witness. An exception is cases when a minor victim or witness or his legal representative objects to this. We believe that such an approach of the legislator allows the court to more effectively assess the admissibility of the results of the named investigative actions, including from the positions of compliance with the rights and legitimate interests of a minor. In this regard, it would be advisable to extend the provisions of part 5 of Article 191 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation to the production of interrogation, face-to-face confrontation, identification, and verification of testimonies carried out with the participation of a minor suspect, defendant. We propose to correct part 6 of Article 425 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation as follows: \\"The order established by this article, as well as by part 5 of Article 191 of this Code, applies also to the conduct of face-to-face confrontation, identification, verification of testimonies of a minor accused, suspect, defendant.\\" Finally, a separate problem of the preliminary investigation is the use of measures of procedural coercion against minors. The provisions of Article 423 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation do not contain special rules distinguishing this category of defendants, suspects, indicating only the fact that when deciding on the choice of a measure of restraint for a minor suspect or defendant, the possibility of giving him under supervision in the order provided for by Article 105 of the Criminal Procedure Code of the Russian Federation should be discussed in each case. According to G.P. Khimicheva, this indicates that it is not always possible \\"to duly take into account the balance between the rights of minors and the objectives of criminal legal proceedings,\\" among which in this case are the provision of a normal course of the process by suppressing and preventing further illegal activities of the accused or suspect, who can hide from the inquiry, investigation or court, continue criminal activity, interfere with the proceedings of the criminal case, as well as ensure the enforcement of the sentence or possible extradition of the person [12, p. 20]. The choice of one or another measure of restraint from the list specified in the law is carried out by the person conducting the proceedings of the criminal case (part 1 of Article 97 